Here is the complete guide for the connection of the cables:

🕒 Real-Time Clock Module (DS3231)
This component keeps track of the time. In addition to the main chip, the module features a slot for a coin cell battery (CR2032), which keeps the time updated even if you unplug the main power supply.

Ground Pin (GND): Connect this to the GND (Ground) pin on the ESP32.

Power Pin (VCC): Connect this to the 3V3 pin on the ESP32 to provide the correct voltage to the module.

Data Pin (SDA): Connect this to the GPIO 21 pin on the ESP32.

Clock Pin (SCL): Connect this to the GPIO 22 pin on the ESP32.

⚡ 2-Channel Relay Module
This module acts as a physical switch to handle the electrical power going to the water pumps.

Ground Pin (GND): Connect this to any free GND pin on the ESP32.

Signal 1 Pin (IN1): Connect this to the GPIO 25 control pin on the ESP32 to control the first pump.

Signal 2 Pin (IN2): Connect this to the GPIO 26 control pin on the ESP32 to control the second pump.

Power Pin (VCC): Connect this to the 5V Out on the UPS board to get the necessary current to make the relays click.

🔋 Power Management Board (UPS v3)
This board brings together the batteries and the solar panel, and distributes power to the entire system. It holds two 18650 lithium batteries in its built-in slot.

Power Output Terminals (5V Out + / -): This is where the power for the whole project comes from. The positive pole (+) connects to the 5V pin on the ESP32 and the VCC pin on the relay. The negative pole (-) connects to the GND pin on the ESP32, creating the common ground line.

Solar Input Terminals (Solar In + / -): The positive pole (+) takes the red wire from the solar panel, while the negative pole (-) takes the black wire from the solar panel.

✂️ Managing and Cutting the Pump Wires (⚠️ Pay Close Attention Here!)
The pumps have two integrated wires: one Red (positive) and one Black (negative).

The Negative Wire (Black): Straight to Ground
Take the black wire from Pump 1 and the black wire from Pump 2.

Join them together (by soldering them or using a wire terminal block).

Connect this joined point directly to the negative pole 5V Out (-) on the UPS board.

The Positive Wire (Red): Cut by the Switch
The positive current is interrupted by the screw terminals of the relay (each channel has three inputs: NO for Normally Open, COM for Common, and NC for Normally Closed).

The Power Bridge: Take a piece of electrical wire and connect it to the positive pole 5V Out (+) on the UPS board. Connect the other end of this wire to the COM terminal of Channel 1 on the relay module. From this exact same terminal, run a small piece of wire (a bridge) into the COM terminal of Channel 2. Tighten the screws: now the power is waiting on both channels.

Connecting the Pumps:

Take the red wire from Pump 1 and insert it into the NO terminal of Channel 1.

Take the red wire from Pump 2 and insert it into the NO terminal of Channel 2.

🧾 Visual Connection Checklist (Every wire you need to run)
To be 100% sure, double-check that you have run exactly these wires:

Wire 1: From DS3231 (GND) to ESP32 (GND).

Wire 2: From DS3231 (VCC) to ESP32 (3V3).

Wire 3: From DS3231 (SDA) to ESP32 (GPIO 21).

Wire 4: From DS3231 (SCL) to ESP32 (GPIO 22).

Wire 5: From Relay Module (GND) to ESP32 (GND).

Wire 6: From Relay Module (IN1) to ESP32 (GPIO 25).

Wire 7: From Relay Module (IN2) to ESP32 (GPIO 26).

Wire 8: From Relay Module (VCC) to UPS (5V Out +).

Wire 9: From UPS (5V Out +) to ESP32 (5V).

Wire 10: From UPS (5V Out -) to ESP32 (GND).

Wire 11: From Solar Panel (Red Wire +) to UPS (Solar In +).

Wire 12: From Solar Panel (Black Wire -) to UPS (Solar In -).

Wire 13: From UPS (5V Out +) to Relay Module (COM 1 terminal, then bridge to COM 2).

Wire 14: From UPS (5V Out -) to Pump 1 Black Wire + Pump 2 Black Wire (joined together).

Wire 15: From Relay Module (NO 1 terminal) to Pump 1 Red Wire.

Wire 16: From Relay Module (NO 2 terminal) to Pump 2 Red Wire.
